  <compounddef id="type-array" kind="page">
    <compoundname>type-array</compoundname>
    <title>Array Variables</title>
    <briefdescription>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>Arrays in Retro Rocket BASIC are collections of variables of the same type, indexed by a <bold>zero-based subscript</bold> in brackets.</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>String arrays end with <computeroutput>$</computeroutput> (e.g. <computeroutput>names$(0)</computeroutput>),</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Real arrays end with <computeroutput>#</computeroutput> (e.g. <computeroutput>values#(10)</computeroutput>),</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Integer arrays have no suffix (e.g. <computeroutput>scores(5)</computeroutput>).</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
<sect1 id="type-array_1declaring-arrays_1s1"><sect2 id="type-array_1declaring-arrays_1s2"><sect3 id="type-array_1declaring-arrays">
<title>Declaring arrays</title><para>Arrays must be created with the <ref refid="DIM" kindref="compound">DIM</ref> statement:</para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">DIM<sp/>names$,<sp/>100</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">DIM<sp/>values#,<sp/>50</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">DIM<sp/>scores,<sp/>200</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>This allocates arrays with the specified number of elements.</para>
<para>Arrays can be resized dynamically with <ref refid="REDIM" kindref="compound">REDIM</ref>:</para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">REDIM<sp/>names$,<sp/>200</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
<sect1 id="type-array_1accessing-elements_1s1"><sect2 id="type-array_1accessing-elements_1s2"><sect3 id="type-array_1accessing-elements">
<title>Accessing elements</title><para>Use a zero-based index to read or write individual elements:</para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">names$(0)<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;Alice&quot;</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">scores(5)<sp/>=<sp/>42</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">values#(10)<sp/>=<sp/>3.14</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
<sect1 id="type-array_1assigning-to-all-elements_1s1"><sect2 id="type-array_1assigning-to-all-elements_1s2"><sect3 id="type-array_1assigning-to-all-elements">
<title>Assigning to all elements</title><para>Assigning to the array name without a subscript initialises <bold>all elements</bold>:</para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">scores<sp/>=<sp/>0</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">names$<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;foo&quot;</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>This sets every element of <computeroutput>scores</computeroutput> to <computeroutput>0</computeroutput> and every element of <computeroutput>names$</computeroutput> to <computeroutput>&quot;foo&quot;</computeroutput>.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
<sect1 id="type-array_1notes-180_1s1"><sect2 id="type-array_1notes-180_1s2"><sect3 id="type-array_1notes-180">
<title>Notes</title><para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Arrays are always contiguous in memory.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Indexes must be within bounds (0 to length–1) or an error occurs.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Resizing with <computeroutput>REDIM</computeroutput> preserves existing values where possible.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
<para><bold>See also:</bold> <ref refid="DIM" kindref="compound">DIM</ref> · <ref refid="REDIM" kindref="compound">REDIM</ref> · <ref refid="PUSH" kindref="compound">PUSH</ref> · <ref refid="POP" kindref="compound">POP</ref> </para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
